 Rituals of Identity takes an innovative approach to the study of Palestine’s modern history by focusing on the Prophet Moses festival from the late Ottoman period through the era of British rule. Halabi explores how the festival served as an arena of competing discourses, with various social groups attempting to control its symbols. Tackling questions about modernity, colonialism, gender relations, and identity, Halabi recounts how peasants, Bedouins, rural women, and Sufis sought to influence the festival even as Ottoman authorities, British colonists, Muslim clerics, and Palestinian national leaders did the same. Drawing on extensive research in Arabic newspapers and Islamic and colonial archives, Halabi reveals how the festival has encapsulated Palestinians’ responses to modernity, colonialism, and the nation’s growing national identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFasts and feastsxIslamxPolitical aspectsxHistory. 0aFasts and feastszJerusalemxHistory. 0aFestivalsxPolitical aspectszJerusalemxHistory. 0aFestivalszJerusalemxHistory. 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimagesxPolitical aspectsxHistory. 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimageszJerusalemxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aPalestine, history, colonialism, Islam, rituals, Sufis, shrines, pilgrimage, Nabi Musa, Jerusalem, British Mandate, Ottoman, Islamic history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press 